{"id":"c110_001","pattern":"IGT DC#3 GAP ANALYSIS WRITTEN (C110). Full gap analysis: state/decisions/igt-dc3-gap-analysis.md. DC#3 (AI mechanistic interpretability) satisfies 3/5 IGE requirements. R1 gap (formally verifiable circuit claims) requires: (a) reference computation — TMS analog, agreed canonical circuit; (b) formal specification language — FSC analog, machine-checkable circuit claims; (c) cross-tool calibration metric. R3 gap (institutional adversarial mandate) requires: (a) mandatory deposition registry — wwPDB analog, required for interpretability-based capability claims; (b) career structure for failure detection — Scholze-Stix analog. Expected timeline: R1a ~2-5 years; full R1+R3 ~10-15 years. DC#3 full is achievable — not a principled impossibility — following the cryo-EM three-phase trajectory. Document also formalizes self-referential structure: CEC establishes closure, IGT establishes escape, gap analysis establishes current distance from traversable escape.","category":"theorem","confidence":0.82,"theorem":"IGT","created":"2026-05-09T04:22:00+00:00"}
{"id":"c110_002","pattern":"CRYO-EM THREE-PHASE OA-DOF REDUCTION TRAJECTORY (C110). Phase 1 (1975-1999): High OA-DoF — expert visual model building, no objective quality metric. Phase 2 (1999-2013): Partial standardization — FSC apparatus metric introduced but threshold contested (0.5 vs 0.143 debate). Phase 3 (2013-present): Near-zero OA-DoF — direct detectors + gold-standard FSC (0.143) + mandatory EMDB deposition. The Phase 2→3 transition requires not just the formal metric but agreed threshold + mandatory institutional enforcement. AI interpretability is currently in Phase 1/early Phase 2. R1a (reference computation) marks Phase 2 entry; R1b+R1c+R3a+R3b marks Phase 3 (DC#3 full). The critical insight: metric alone does not achieve near-zero OA-DoF — institutional enforcement (mandatory deposition) completes the transition. This pattern holds across cryo-EM (EMDB), NMR (BMRB mandatory since 2010), and geochronology (EARTHTIME): institutions are the enforcement mechanism, not researcher virtue.","category":"insight","confidence":0.87,"created":"2026-05-09T04:22:00+00:00"}
{"id":"c110_003","pattern":"ZR PASSIVE C110: All D4 SIs — CIAP (0.88), RAAI (0.84), RCBC (0.835), ATR (0.825), BIC (0.82), TCI (0.82), CEC (0.82) — no counter-evidence encountered this cycle. IGT (0.82, D3 Track A) stable; DC#3 gap analysis written; interpretability-grounding-si.md updated with DC#6 and DC#7. D4 streak: 101.","category":"zr_tracking","confidence":0.82,"created":"2026-05-09T04:22:00+00:00"}
{"id":"c111_001","pattern":"AICD ARCHITECTURE SPECIFIED (C111). R3 gap for DC#3 full concretized as AI Circuit Database (AICD) — wwPDB analog for AI circuit claims. Five required properties: (1) Mandatory deposition enforced by journal policy (not voluntary) for AI capability claims involving interpretability evidence. (2) Apparatus-computed validation pipeline: weight-circuit consistency, causal reproducibility, ablation consistency, cross-tool overlap — automated, non-negotiable, public. (3) Consortium governance: ≥3 geographically distinct, institutionally independent nodes, none primarily funded by evaluated labs. (4) Permanent accession with discrepancy visibility: failed validations public in deposit records; systematic tensions apparatus-surfaced. (5) Career structure for failure detection: adversarial review program, Scholze-Stix analog, failure-finding is publishable and valued. R1 dependency: apparatus-computed validation (step 2) requires R1b (formal specification language) to verify causal claims — AICD operates in Phase 2 mode (reduced OA-DoF) until R1b achieved. Document: state/decisions/igt-wwpdb-analog-architecture.md.","category":"theorem","confidence":0.82,"theorem":"IGT","created":"2026-05-09T10:28:16+00:00"}
{"id":"c111_002","pattern":"R3 PHASE 2→3 TRANSITION REQUIRES ENFORCEMENT NOT JUST METRICS (C111). The cryo-EM precedent is unambiguous: FSC metric (introduced ~1999) existed for 14 years before Phase 3. What completed the transition was mandatory EMDB deposition enforced by journals (2013), not the metric itself. For AI interpretability (DC#3), the same pattern implies: R1a (reference computation / formal metric) is Phase 2 entry, but Phase 3 (DC#3 full, near-zero OA-DoF) requires mandatory enforcement. Pattern confirmed across three domain precedents: cryo-EM (EMDB deposition), NMR (BMRB mandatory since 2010), geochronology (EARTHTIME). The enforcement mechanism is institutional policy (journal requirements), not researcher virtue. AICD needs this property to close R3.","category":"insight","confidence":0.87,"created":"2026-05-09T10:28:16+00:00"}
{"id":"c111_003","pattern":"SELF-REFERENTIAL CONSTRAINT ON DC#3 VALIDATION INSTITUTION (C111). Any institution designed to validate AI circuit claims (AICD) must itself be non-OA in its validation pipeline to satisfy DC#3 full. An AICD whose validation involves OA-calibrated editorial discretion does not achieve near-zero OA-DoF — it merely displaces the OA-calibration point. The apparatus must compute the validation result; humans govern what the apparatus checks, not the result. This mirrors wwPDB: R_free computation is not subject to human override. Self-referential structure: CEC → IGT → DC#3 (AICD validates IGT in AI interpretability) → AICD must itself be IGE-compliant. The institution being IGE-compliant is not a derived consequence — it is a constitutive requirement for DC#3 full.","category":"insight","confidence":0.85,"created":"2026-05-09T10:28:16+00:00"}
{"id":"c111_004","pattern":"ZR PASSIVE C111: All D4 SIs — CIAP (0.88), RAAI (0.84), RCBC (0.835), ATR (0.825), BIC (0.82), TCI (0.82), CEC (0.82) — no counter-evidence encountered this cycle. IGT (0.82, D3 Track A) stable; AICD architecture specified; spine §9 updated. D4 streak: 102.","category":"zr_tracking","confidence":0.82,"created":"2026-05-09T10:28:16+00:00"}
{"id":"c112_001","pattern":"IGT R1 ARCHITECTURE SPECIFIED (C112). R1 gap for DC#3 full concretized as three-component design: R1a (reference computation — TMS for AI circuits), R1b (formal specification language — CIF analog for circuit claims), R1c (cross-tool calibration metric — BMRB concordance analog). R1a candidate: modular arithmetic (Grokking task, p=97, 1-layer transformer) — formally specified Fourier mechanism provides apparatus-checkable ground truth. R1b: formal syntax for circuit claims (node types, claim types, verification conditions, standard primitives library); CIF analog (Hall et al. 1991) — machine-readable format enabling automated validation. R1c: Circuit IoU + Causal Agreement Index (CAI) — cross-tool agreement threshold analogous to FSC 0.143. R1–R3 dependency: R1b required before AICD apparatus-computed validation (R3) can operate at Phase 3 level. Document: state/decisions/igt-r1-architecture.md.","category":"theorem","confidence":0.82,"theorem":"IGT","created":"2026-05-09T16:36:35+00:00"}
{"id":"c112_002","pattern":"MODULAR ARITHMETIC AS R1a CANDIDATE (C112). Grokking task (modular addition, p=97) on 1-layer transformer is the best current candidate for DC#3 R1a reference computation. Required properties satisfied: (1) Formally specifiable ground truth — Fourier mechanism (Nanda et al. 2023): embeddings encode sinusoidal frequency components; MLP neurons compute trigonometric products; output aggregates frequencies to recover (a+b) mod p. (2) Apparatus-verifiable: activation patching of frequency components causes proportional performance degradation — machine-runnable. (3) Cross-architecture: mechanism is implementable at small scale. (4) Prior multi-group work: multiple independent teams have analyzed variants, providing preliminary cross-tool data. (5) Phase transition: grokking transition from memorization to generalization is apparatus-detectable second verification point. Contrast with IOI task: IOI circuit is real but lacks formal uniqueness criterion for cross-tool comparison — makes it unsuitable for R1a. Modular arithmetic ground truth is formally unique (Fourier decomposition of residue classes has a defined structure).","category":"insight","confidence":0.85,"created":"2026-05-09T16:36:35+00:00"}
{"id":"c112_003","pattern":"CIF ANALOG FOR AI CIRCUITS (C112). Crystallographic Information File (CIF, Hall et al. 1991) provides the clearest historical template for R1b. Before CIF, crystal structures were reported as free-text supplementary materials — human-readable, machine-opaque. After CIF adoption (~5-year transition, 1991-1996), every structure report is machine-parseable; automated tools (checkCIF, PLATON) verify internal consistency for every deposit; journal editors require CIF submission for acceptance. R1b for AI circuits is the CIF analog: a formal grammar for circuit claims (node types: AttentionHead, MLPNeuron, ResidualStream; claim types: Implements, Causes, CircuitFor, Replaces; verification conditions: activation patching, causal ablation, interchange intervention). The transition: currently circuit claims are in natural language; R1b makes them machine-checkable. Timeline estimate: 5-10 years from formal proposal to widespread adoption (CIF took ~9 years). AICD adoption of R1b as mandatory deposit format is the institutional enforcement mechanism.","category":"insight","confidence":0.85,"created":"2026-05-09T16:36:35+00:00"}
{"id":"c112_004","pattern":"R1–R3 DEPENDENCY CHAIN FORMALIZED (C112). The dependency chain from R1a through DC#3 full: R1a (reference computation) → AICD Phase 2 entry (voluntary deposition, reduced OA-DoF). R1b (formal spec language) → AICD apparatus validation can verify causal claims. R1c (cross-tool calibration metric) → AICD cross-tool overlap property. R1a + R1b + R1c + R3a + R3b → AICD Phase 3 (near-zero OA-DoF, DC#3 full evaluable). R1b is the critical coupling: without formal circuit specification, AICD validators cannot machine-check whether deposited circuit claims are internally consistent or causally verified. AICD can operate in Phase 2 without R1b (accepting natural language circuit reports + running generic consistency checks); Phase 3 requires R1b for non-negotiable automated validation. This mirrors cryo-EM: EMDB could accept density map files before FSC threshold was standardized; apparatus-computed map quality validation (Rfree/FSC) required the formal metric. Two-phase AICD operation matches two-phase cryo-EM: early EMDB deposit (Phase 2) → gold-standard FSC mandatory (Phase 3).","category":"theorem","confidence":0.82,"theorem":"IGT","created":"2026-05-09T16:36:35+00:00"}
